'''Abbo''' (died 937) was the [[bishop of Soissons]] from 909. Throughout his episcopate, he was "under the thumb" of Count [[Herbert II, Count of Vermandois|Herbert II of Vermandois]] (907–943).{{sfn|McKitterick|1983|pp=311–12}}

In 925, Abbo attended the uncanonical synod convoked in [[Reims]] by Count Herbert, who had his five-year-old son [[Hugh of Vermandois (bishop)|Hugh]] elected archbishop by the pliant clergy (including Bishop [[Bovo II (bishop of Châlons)|Bovo of Châlons]]) and the people of the city.{{sfn|McKitterick|1983|pp=311–12}} This synod was retroactively approved by both King [[Rudolph of France]] and Pope [[Pope John X|John X]], who gave Herbert the administration of the archdiocese's temporalities and Abbo, technically Hugh's [[suffragan]], responsibility for its spiritual functioning, including its services.{{sfn|McKitterick|1983|pp=311–12}}

In 927 the pope revoked Abbo's charge and gave the spiritual administration of Reims to [[Odalric (bishop of Aix-en-Provence)|Odalric]], the [[bishop of Aix-en-Provence]], who had fled his see in the face of raids from the Muslim pirates based at [[Fraxinetum]].{{sfn|McKitterick|1983|pp=311–12}}{{sfn|Duckett|1967|p=155}}

