{{Unreferenced|date=February 2010}} {{Infobox Congressman |name = Isaac Wildrick |image name = |state1 = [[New Jersey]] |district1 = [[New Jersey's 3rd congressional district|3rd]] |party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] |term1 = March 4, 1849 &ndash; March 3, 1853 |preceded1 = [[Joseph E. Edsall]] |succeeded1 = [[Samuel Lilly]] |office2 = Member of the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] |term2 = 1882-1885 |birth_date = March 3, 1803 |birth_place = [[Frelinghuysen Township, New Jersey]] |death_date ={{Death date and age|1892|3|22|1803|3|3}} |death_place = [[Blairstown, New Jersey]] |spouse = |profession = Politician |religion = |footnotes = }} '''Isaac Wildrick''' (March 3, 1803 in [[Frelinghuysen Township, New Jersey]] &ndash; March 22, 1892 in [[Blairstown, New Jersey]]) was an American [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] politician, who represented {{ushr|New Jersey|3}} in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1849 to 1853.
Wildrick was born in Marksboro (in [[Frelinghuysen Township, New Jersey]]) on March 3, 1803. He attended the common schools, and engaged in agricultural pursuits near Blairstown. He was constable from 1827 to 1832, coroner from 1829 to 1831, [[Justice of the Peace]] from 1834 to 1839, judge in 1839, sheriff from 1839 to 1841 and director of the county poorhouse from 1842 to 1848. He was a member of the [[Board of Chosen Freeholders]] from 1845 to 1848.
Wildrick was elected as a Democrat to the [[31st United States Congress|Thirty-first]] and [[32nd United States Congress|Thirty-second]] Congresses, serving in office from March 4, 1849, to March 3, 1853, but was not a candidate for renomination in 1852.
After leaving Congress, he resumed agricultural pursuits. He was again a freeholder from 1856 to 1859, and was a member of the [[New Jersey General Assembly]] from 1882 to 1885. He died in Blairstown on March 22, 1892, and was interred in the Presbyterian Cemetery in the [[Marksboro, New Jersey|Marksboro]] section of Frelinghuysen Township.
