'''Izaak Aaronowicz''', born '''Izaak ben Aron Prostitz''' (died 1629<ref name="Lelewel1858">{{cite book|last=Lelewel|first=Joachim|title=Polska dzieje i rzeczy jej|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEpKAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA69|accessdate=15 July 2012|year=1858|publisher=Zupanskiego|page=69}}</ref>) was a [[Polish people|Polish]] [[author]] and [[printer (publishing)|printer]] of [[Biblical Hebrew|Hebrew]] books.

He came from Prostic in [[Moravia]], and moved to [[Krakow]]. In addition to many works of Hebrew, appreciated by [[Orientalism|Orientalists]], is his edition of the [[Babylonian Talmud]] (1603-1605) in 12 volumes. Fluent in Hebrew and "learned in the [[Bible]]," he wrote several books on religious figures.<ref>Jerzy Alexandrowicz (red.): Wielka encyklopedia powszechna ilustrowana. Warszawa: Saturnin Józef Sikorski, 1890-1891.</ref>

