{{Other people}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}} {{Use South African English|date=August 2012}} {{Infobox person | name = Kevin Carter | image = KevinCarter.jpg | caption = | birthname = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1960|9|13}} | birth_place = [[Johannesburg]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1994|7|24|1960|9|13}} | death_place = [[Parkmore]], Johannesburg, South Africa | occupation = [[photojournalism|Photojournalist]] |notable_works = ''[[The vulture and the little girl]]'' }}
'''Kevin Carter''' (13 September 1960 – 24 July 1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jul/30/kevin-carter-photojournalist-obituary-archive-1994|title=Photojournalist Kevin Carter dies - obituary: from the archive, 30 July 1994|first=Eamonn|last=McCabe|date=30 July 2014|website=the Guardian|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref> was a [[South Africa]]n [[photojournalism|photojournalist]] and member of the [[Bang-Bang Club]]. He was the recipient of a [[Pulitzer Prize for Photography|Pulitzer Prize]] for his photograph depicting the [[1993 Sudan famine|1993 famine in Sudan]]. He died by suicide at the age of 33. His story is depicted in the 2010 feature film ''[[The Bang Bang Club (film)|The Bang-Bang Club]]'', in which he was played by [[Taylor Kitsch]].
== Early life == Kevin Carter was born in [[Johannesburg]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]] and grew up in a middle-class, whites-only neighborhood. As a child, he occasionally saw police raids to arrest blacks who were illegally living in the area. He said later that he questioned how his parents, a [[Catholicism|Catholic]], "liberal" family, could be what he described as 'lackadaisical' about fighting against [[apartheid]].{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|pp=39–41}}
After high school, Carter dropped out of his studies to become a [[pharmacist]] and was drafted into the [[South African Army|army]]. To escape from the infantry, he enlisted in the [[South African Air Force|Air Force]] in which he served four years. In 1980, he witnessed a black mess-hall waiter being insulted. Carter defended the man, resulting in him being badly beaten by the other servicemen. He then went [[absent without leave]], attempting to start a new life as a radio disc-jockey named "David". This, however, proved more difficult than he had anticipated. Soon after, he decided to serve out the rest of his required military service. After witnessing the [[Church Street bombing]] in Pretoria in 1983, he decided to become a news photographer and journalist.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|pp=39–41}}
== Early work == Carter had started to work as a weekend sports photographer in 1983. In 1984, he moved on to work for the ''[[The Star (South Africa)|Johannesburg Star]]'', went on exposing the brutality of apartheid.
Carter was the first to photograph a public execution "[[necklacing]]" by black Africans in South Africa in the mid-1980s. Carter later spoke of the images: "I was appalled at what they were doing. But then people started talking about those pictures... then I felt that maybe my actions hadn't been at all bad. Being a witness to something this horrible wasn't necessarily such a bad thing to do."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timporter.com/firstdraft/archives/000071.html|title=First Draft by Tim Porter: Covering War in a Free Society|website=www.timporter.com|accessdate=3 November 2018}}</ref>
== In Sudan == In March 1993, Robert Hadley of the UN [[Operation Lifeline Sudan]] offered [[João Silva (photographer)|João Silva]] the opportunity to travel to Sudan and report about the famine in South Sudan embedding with the rebels in that area's civil war.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|p=110}} Silva told Carter, who felt it was an opportunity to expand his freelance career and use work as a way to address personal problems.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|pp=109-110}} Operation Lifeline Sudan had been having funding difficulties,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Karim|first1=Ataul|last2=Duffield|first2=Mark|last3=Jaspers|first3=Susanne|last4=Hendrie|first4=Barbara|title=Operation Lifeline Sudan – A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/284727714_Operation_Lifeline_Sudan_-_A_review|website=www.researchgate.net|date=June 1996|publisher=ResearchGate|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref> and the UN believed that publicizing the area's famine and needs would help aid organizations sustain funding. Silva and Carter were apolitical and desiring only to photograph.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|p=113}}
After flying to [[Nairobi]], the two found out that new fighting in Sudan would force them to wait in that city indefinitely. During this time, Carter made a day trip with the UN to [[Juba]] in the south Sudan to photograph a barge with food aid for the region. Soon afterward, the UN received permission from a rebel group to fly food aid to [[Ayod]]. Hadley invited Silva and Carter to fly there with him.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|p=114}} Once in Ayod, Silva and Carter separated to shoot photos of famine victims, discussing between themselves the shocking situations they were witnessing. Silva found rebel soldiers who could take him to someone in authority. Carter joined him. One of the soldiers, who did not speak English, was interested in Carter's wristwatch. Carter gave him the cheap watch as a gift.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|p=116}} The soldiers served as their bodyguards.{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|pp=152–153|loc=Marinovich explains the soldiers as bodyguards}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/201137365|title=Carter and soldiers|website=www.vimeo.com}}</ref>
=== Pulitzer Prize photograph in Sudan=== {{main|The vulture and the little girl}} Carter shot an image of what appeared to be a little girl, fallen to the ground from hunger, while a vulture lurked on the ground nearby. He told Silva he was shocked by the situation he had just photographed, and had chased the vulture away. A few minutes later, Carter and Silva boarded a small UN plane and left Ayod for [[Kongor]].{{sfn|Marinovich|Silva|2000|p=118}}
Sold to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the photograph first appeared on 26 March 1993, and syndicated worldwide. Hundreds of people contacted the newspaper to ask the fate of the girl. The paper said that according to Carter, "she recovered enough to resume her trek after the vulture was chased away" but that it was unknown whether she reached the UN food center."<ref>{{cite news|title=Editors' Note|work=The New York Times|accessdate=1 September 2016|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/30/nyregion/editors-note-513893.html}}</ref> In April 1994, the photograph won the [[Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography]].<ref>http://www.pulitzer.org/winners/kevin-carter-free-lance-photographer Pulitzer Prize</ref>
In 2011, the child's father revealed the child was actually a boy, Kong Nyong, and had been taken care of by the UN food aid station. Nyong had died four years prior, c. 2007, of "fevers", according to his family.<ref name="Kong Nyong, el niño que sobrevivió al buitre">{{cite news|title=Kong Nyong, el niño que sobrevivió al buitre / Kong Nyong, The Boy Who Survived the Vulture|first=Alberto|last= Rojas|date=21 February 2011|accessdate=29 August 2017|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2011/02/18/comunicacion/1298054483.html|work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]| language=Spanish|archivedate=30 June 2017|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170630053614/http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2011/02/18/comunicacion/1298054483.html| deadurl=no}}</ref>
== Other work == In March 1994 Carter took a photograph of the three [[Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging]] members being shot during their [[1994 Bophuthatswana crisis|abortive invasion]] of [[Bophuthatswana]] just before the [[South African general election, 1994|South African election]]. Halfway through the incident, Carter ran out of film, but still got enough pictures to supply newspapers around the world. Eamonn McCabe of ''[[The Guardian]]'' said: "It was a picture that made nearly every front page in the world, the one real photograph of the whole campaign."<ref>{{cite web|author=Eamonn McCabe |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jul/30/kevin-carter-photojournalist-obituary-archive-1994 |title=Photojournalist Kevin Carter dies – obituary: from the archive, 30 July 1994; Media |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]'' |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>
== Awards == In April 1994, [[The vulture and the little girl|Carter's photograph]] of a starving [[Second Sudanese Civil War|Sudanese]] child being eyed by a vulture won the [[Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography]].<ref name="time-1994">{{cite journal |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=12 September 1994 |volume=144 |number=11 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,981431,00.html |title=The Life and Death of Kevin Carter |last=MacLeod |first=Scott |location=Johannesburg |accessdate=27 October 2015 |subscription=yes}}</ref>
== Death == On 24 July 1994, Carter drove to [[Parkmore]] near the Field and Study Centre, an area where he used to play as a child, and committed suicide by taping one end of a hose to his pickup truck’s exhaust pipe and running the other end to the driver's side window. He died of [[carbon monoxide poisoning]] at the age of 33. Portions of Carter's suicide note read:<ref name="time-1994" />
{{quote|I'm really, really sorry. The pain of life overrides the joy to the point that joy does not exist. ...depressed ... without phone ... money for rent ... money for child support ... money for debts ... money!!! ... I am haunted by the vivid memories of killings & corpses & anger & pain ... of starving or wounded children, of trigger-happy madmen, often police, of killer executioners ... I have gone to join Ken if I am that lucky.}}
The final line is a reference to his recently deceased colleague [[Ken Oosterbroek]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}
The 1996 song "[[Kevin Carter (song)|Kevin Carter]]" by rock band [[Manic Street Preachers]], from their fourth album ''[[Everything Must Go (Manic Street Preachers album)|Everything Must Go]]'', was inspired by Carter's life and suicide.{{snf|Newark|2013|p=96}} The lyrics were written by [[Richey Edwards]] shortly before [[Richey Edwards#Disappearance|his own disappearance]].
