{{DEFAULTSORT:Carter, Kevin}} [[Category:1960 births]] [[Category:1994 deaths]] [[Category:Journalists who committed suicide]] [[Category:South African people of British descent]] [[Category:The New York Times visual journalists]] [[Category:People from Johannesburg]] [[Category:Photographers who committed suicide]] [[Category:Male suicides]] [[Category:South African photojournalists]] [[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography winners]] [[Category:War photographers]] [[Category:South African Roman Catholics]] [[Category:South African photographers]] [[Category:Suicides by carbon monoxide poisoning]] [[Category:Suicides in South Africa]] [[Category:White South African people]] [[Category:Bang-Bang Club]] [[Category:Deaths by poisoning|Carbon monoxide poisoning]]

'''Lucius Aemilius Carus''' (fl. 2nd century AD) was a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] military officer and [[Senate of the Roman Empire|senator]] who served as ''[[Roman consul|consul suffectus]]'' for one of the ''[[nundinium|nundinia]]'' in the first half of AD 144, with [[Quintus Egrilius Plarianus]] as his colleague.<ref>[[Werner Eck]], "Die Fasti consulares der Regungszeit des Antoninus Pius, eine Bestandsaufnahme seit Géza Alföldys Konsulat und Senatorenstand" in ''Studia epigraphica in memoriam Géza Alföldy'', hg. W. Eck, B. Feher, and P. Kovács (Bonn, 2013), p. 74</ref> His life is known primarily through inscriptions.<ref>Most notably, {{CIL|6|1333}}</ref>

==Biography==
The son of Lucius and a member of the [[Roman tribe]] ''Camilia'', Carus' career began with his appointment to the ''[[decemviri stlitibus judicandis]]'', one of the four boards of the ''[[vigintiviri]]''; membership in one of these four boards was a preliminary and required first step toward gaining entry into the Roman Senate. This was followed by serving as a [[military tribune]], firstly of the [[Legio VIII Augusta]], at the time stationed at ''[[Argentoratum]]'' ([[Strasbourg]]), then of the [[Legio IX Hispana]], sometime after AD 122.{{sfn|Kleb|1897|p=27}}<ref>Cowan, R. ''Roman Legionary AD 69-161'' (2013), p. 10</ref> Returning to [[Rome]], Carus began his climb up the series of Republican magistracies: first appointed ''[[quaestor]]'' to the Emperor, then [[Tribune of the Plebs|Plebeian Tribune]] before achieving the [[Praetor]]ship.{{sfn|Kleb|1897|p=27}}

Returning to the military sphere, Carus was granted the rank of ''[[Legatus legionis]]'', commanding the [[Legio XXX Ulpia Victrix]]. Anthony Birley notes this was unusual assignment, for Legio XXX and Legio IX were both stationed in the same province, [[Germania Inferior]], and men were rarely assigned command of a legion in the same army as they had held a tribunate; Birley could only list 14 men with that distinction.<ref>Birley, ''The Fasti of Roman Britain'', (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1981), pp. 17f</ref> He returned to civilian life, serving as curator of the [[Via Flaminia]]. His next assignment was as ''[[Legatus Augusti pro praetore]]'' (or governor) of the [[Roman province]] of [[Arabia Petraea]] from AD 142 to 143.{{sfn|Campbell|2006|p=62}} In 144, he was appointed [[Roman consul|suffect consul]], and this was followed up with an appointment as imperial ''[[Censor (ancient Rome)#Census beyond Rome|censitor]]'' of [[Gallia Lugdunensis]]. Finally, Carus was made ''Legatus Augusti pro praetore'', or governor, of [[Cappadocia (Roman province)|Cappadocia]].{{sfn|Campbell|2006|p=62}}

Carus was a member of the ''[[Quindecimviri sacris faciundis]]'', the ''[[collegia|collegium]]'' of Roman priests entrusted with the care of the [[Sibylline oracles]], and the ''[[sodales|sodales Flaviales]]'', a less prominent ''collegium''.{{sfn|Campbell|2006|p=62}}

== Family ==
Carus' son, also named Lucius Aemilius Carus, was ''Legatus Augusti pro praetore'' of the province of ''[[Roman Dacia|Tres Daciae]]'' in AD 174/175, and suffect consul at some point between 170 and 175.<ref>Géza Alföldy, ''Konsulat und Senatorenstand unter der Antoninen'' (Bonn: Rudolf Habelt Verlag, 1977), p. 224 and note</ref>

==Sources==
